# Autoformat code level 1

We ave written a text in a programming language that uses brackets `{}`as a block separator, `\n` as new line separator and ` ` as whitespace character. We want to be sure that the intentation is correct. 

## Input parameters: 

* *text*: Type string. 
* *spaces*: Type integer. `spaces > 0`. 

## Task: 

If the *text* is inconsistent with opening and closing brackets, the function should return the message "Syntax error" as a string. I recommend this [kata](https://www.codewars.com/kata/52774a314c2333f0a7000688) for this particular case. 

The function must correctly adjusts the indentation of every line of *text*. One indentation level must have as many whitespaces as *spaces* indicates, two levels must have double, and so on. 

You should not modify the *text* given except for adding or removing whitespaces in the begining of a line following this rules: 

* Each line should have N times *spaces* of whitespaces at the begining. To calculate N you should take into consideration **only the previous lines**: where N = amount of opening brackets `{` minus the amount of closing brackets `}`. 

* If the actual line begins with zero or more whitespaces and an closing bracket `}`, this bracket, and only this first one, should be taken into account for the calculation of N by adding an additional closing bracket to the result.

## Examples: 

### First Example

#### Input

```
text = "var size = 5;\n\nfor(var i=0; i<size.lenght; i++){\nfor(var j=0; j<size.lenght; j++){\nconsole.log(i+j);\n}\n}"
spaces = 2
```

```
var size = 5;

for(var i=0; i<size.lenght; i++){
for(var j=0; j<size.lenght; j++){
console.log(i+j);
}
}
```

#### Output

```python
result = "var size = 5;\n\nfor(var i=0; i<size.lenght; i++){\n  for(var j=0; j<size.lenght; j++){\n    console.log(i+j);\n  }\n}"
```

```
var size = 5;

for(var i=0; i<size.lenght; i++){
  for(var j=0; j<size.lenght; j++){
    console.log(i+j);
  }
}
```

### Second Example

#### Input

```python
text = "  var result = 0;\n\nfor(var i=0; i<size.lenght; i++){\n        result = result + i;\n}\nif (result > 10){\nconsole.log(result);\n    }"
spaces = 4
```

```
  var result = 0;

for(var i=0; i<size.lenght; i++){
        result = result + i;
}
if (result > 10){
console.log(result);
    }
```

#### Output

```python
result = "var result = 0;\n\nfor(var i=0; i<size.lenght; i++){\n    result = result + i;\n}\nif (result > 10){\n    console.log(result);\n}"
```

```
var result = 0;

for(var i=0; i<size.lenght; i++){
    result = result + i;
}
if (result > 10){
    console.log(result);
}
```

### Third Example.

#### Input. 

```python
text = "if (result > 10){\nconsole.log(result);"
spaces = 4
```

```
